<!--  PART 1 — DATA AUTHENTICATION & VALIDATION  (Reading + Q)     -->
<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="section-wrap">
  <div class="section-head"><div class="snum">Part 1</div><h2>Data Authentication &amp; Validation</h2></div>
  <div class="section-body">

    <div class="reading-block">
      <h3>Why does data integrity matter?</h3>
      <p>When someone agrees to a contract—like a car lease or apartment rental—they sign their name to authenticate the document. But what if someone sends you a <em>file</em> on a computer? How do you know it's authentic?</p>
      <p>When you receive a file from a friend, you need to verify that it really came from them <strong>and</strong> that the file is in its original, unaltered form. A file could be changed or corrupted while in transit, while being copied, or while in storage. Even files that <em>look</em> the same can be different in their content.</p>
      <p>The most common way to authenticate and validate files is to use mathematical encryption functions called <strong>cryptographic hash functions</strong>. A hash function creates a <em>fixed-size representation</em> of data that is unique to that data. Any minor change to the data results in a completely different hash value.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="response-area">
