<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<!--  PART 2 — HASHING  (Reading + Q)                             -->
<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="section-wrap">
  <div class="section-head"><div class="snum">Part 2</div><h2>Hashing</h2></div>
  <div class="section-body">

    <div class="reading-block">
      <h3>What is a cryptographic hash function?</h3>
      <p>A cryptographic hash function (called <strong>hashing</strong>) is an algorithm with two key characteristics:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>It maps data of any size to a fixed-size string</strong> (the hash value). Whether you hash a single word or an entire hard drive, the output is always the same length.</li>
        <li><strong>It uses a one-way function.</strong> A one-way function is easy to compute in one direction but infeasible to reverse. You cannot calculate the original data from the hash alone.</li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin-top:10px;">The input to a hash function is called the <strong>message</strong>. The output is called the <strong>message digest</strong> (or simply, the hash). Notice how even a tiny change produces a completely different hash:</p>
      <div class="hash-example"><div class="he-input">The quick brown fox</div><div class="he-arrow">→</div><div class="he-output">48E195AB</div></div>
      <div class="hash-example"><div class="he-input">The quick brown fob</div><div class="he-arrow">→</div><div class="he-output">20CFC056</div></div>
      <div class="callout">
        <strong>Two ways to crack a hash</strong>
        You can attempt a <em>brute-force search</em> by trying all possible inputs, or use a <em>rainbow table</em>—a pre-built lookup table of known hash values—to try to find a match. Both methods are computationally expensive for strong hashes.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="reading-block">
      <h3>The 5 properties of an ideal hash function</h3>
      <div class="prop-grid">
        <div class="prop-card"><strong>1. Deterministic</strong>The same message always produces the same hash value, every time.</div>
        <div class="prop-card"><strong>2. Fast to compute</strong>Calculating a hash value for any message should be quick.</div>
        <div class="prop-card"><strong>3. One-way (irreversible)</strong>It is infeasible to reverse a hash to find the original message.</div>
        <div class="prop-card"><strong>4. Avalanche effect</strong>A tiny change to the message (even one character) produces a completely different hash.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="prop-card" style="margin-top:0"><strong>5. Collision-resistant</strong>It is extremely unlikely that two different messages will produce the same hash value (called a <em>collision</em>).</div>
      <div class="callout" style="margin-top:12px">
        <strong>Why collisions are rare</strong>
        With a 32-bit hash there are 2<sup>32</sup> (~4.3 billion) possible values. A 64-bit hash has 2<sup>64</sup> (~18.4 quintillion) possible values. This makes accidental collisions virtually impossible for real-world use.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="reading-block">
      <h3>Collisions &amp; The Birthday Problem</h3>
      <p>While hash collisions are extremely rare, they are theoretically possible. The <strong>birthday problem</strong> is a statistical puzzle: in a room of just 23 people, there is a ~50% chance that two people share the same birthday. With 30 people it rises to over 70%. At 41 people, over 90%.</p>
      <p>This happens because what matters is the number of <em>pairs</em>, not the number of people. With 23 people there are 253 possible pairs [formula: n(n−1)/2]. Each pair is a chance at a match.</p>
      <p>The same logic applies to hashes: as the number of hashes grows, the odds of a collision increase—but because hash <em>spaces</em> are astronomically large (billions to quintillions of possible values), reaching a meaningful collision probability requires an impractical number of hashes.</p>
      <div class="callout">
        <strong>Key insight</strong>
        The birthday problem involves any two <em>random</em> inputs colliding—not one specific input matching another. A colliding hash would likely represent completely unreadable, nonsensical data rather than a meaningful file.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="reading-block">
      <h3>MD5 vs SHA-1 — Common Hash Algorithms</h3>
      <p>The two most common hash algorithms used in digital forensics are <strong>MD5</strong> (Message Digest 5) and <strong>SHA-1</strong> (Secure Hash Algorithm 1). Both have all five properties of an ideal hash function, but differ in strength and speed.</p>
      <table class="tbl" style="margin-top:10px">
        <thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>MD5</th><th>SHA-1</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Digest length</td><td>128 bits</td><td>160 bits</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Security level</td><td>Less secure</td><td>More secure</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Iterations to produce hash</td><td>64</td><td>80</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Speed</td><td>Faster</td><td>Slower</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Operations to find original message</td><td>2<sup>128</sup></td><td>2<sup>160</sup></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Operations to find any collision</td><td>2<sup>64</sup></td><td>2<sup>80</sup></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Successful attacks reported</td><td>Yes (collisions known)</td><td>Not yet reported</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="response-area">
      <h3>Check Your Understanding</h3>
      <div class="q">
        <label><span class="qn">Q3.</span> List the 5 properties of an ideal hash function from memory (don't peek!).</label>
        <textarea rows="5" placeholder="1. &#10;2. &#10;3. &#10;4. &#10;5. "></textarea>
      </div>
      <div class="q">
        <label><span class="qn">Q4.</span> Explain the birthday problem in your own words. How does it relate to hash collisions?</label>
        <textarea rows="3" placeholder="Your answer…"></textarea>
      </div>
      <div class="q">
        <label><span class="qn">Q5 (Reflection).</span> Why is the birthday problem <em>not</em> a major practical concern for modern hash algorithms like SHA-1?</label>
        <textarea rows="3" placeholder="Hint: think about the size of the hash space…"></textarea>
      </div>
      <div class="q">
        <label><span class="qn">Q6.</span> Using the formula n(n−1)/2, calculate the number of pairs in a group of 23 people. Show your work.</label>
        <textarea rows="3" placeholder="Work: &#10;&#10;Answer: "></textarea>
